Tycho Brahe's Mars data
description: Over the course of 18 years, Brahe collected data of unprecedented quality and extent on the motions of Mars and other celestial bodies. His assistant Johannes Kepler (suspected by some of poisoning Brahe) later used Brahe's work to derive his laws of planetary motion.

name: 1790 U.S. Census
description: The first U.S. Census asked 6 questions. By 1940, it had grown to 50. Over the 20th century, improvements in statistical sampling meant that, for many questions, the Census Bureau could get good estimates by asking just a small subset of residents. In 2010 the questionnaire was pared back to only 10 questions.

name: Hipparcos star dataset
description: From 1989 to 1993, the Hipparcos satellite conducted high-precision astrometry, measuring the motions of celestial objects through parallax. The data published in 1997 catalogued more than 118,200 stars.

name: E. coli genome
description: The bacterium e. coli is one of our oldest friends: it typically colonizes newborns within 40 hours.

name: Bacteriophage MS2 RNA genome
description: This RNA virus was the first genome ever sequenced, by Walter Fiers at the University of Ghent.

name: Phage Phi-X174 genome
description: Fred Sanger completed the first DNA genome sequence.

name: Haemophilus influenzae genome
description: This bacterium, once mistakenly blamed for influenza, was sequenced by Craig Venter's team at the Institute for Genomic Research.

name: Saccharomyces cerevisiae
description: This oft-used yeast became the first eukaryote to be sequenced when an international team published its genome in Science.

name: Netflix Prize data
description: Netflix released a massive trove of anonymous users' movie ratings and offered $1 million to anyone who could improve their recommendation algorithm by at least 10%. The prize was ultimately claimed in 2009 by a team of seven. Netflix never ended up using the improved algorithm, because the shift from DVD rentals to online streaming dramatically changed viewer behavior: their picks became less aspirational, more about instant gratification.

name: Human genome
description: Essentially-complete human genomes were released in 2000 by the Human Genome Project and Celera Genomics. For the sake of privacy, they were composites of genome donors. In 2007, Craig Venter became the first individual to publish his own genome.

description: The first U.S. Census asked 6 questions. By 1940, it had grown to 50. Over the 20th century, improvements in statistical sampling meant that, for many questions, the Census Bureau could get good estimates by asking just a small subset of residents. In 2010 the questionnaire was pared back to only 10 questions.

name: Walmart store sales
description: This particular set of sales data was released by Walmart for a predictive data science competition on the machine learning site Kaggle.

name: MNIST handwritten digits
description: Derived from earlier National Institute of Standards and Technology data by a trio from NYU, Google, and Microsoft, these images of handwritten numerals are used to train handwriting-recognition models.

name: 1000 Genomes
description: The deceptively-named 1000 Genomes project in fact aims to collect the genomes of 2,600 people from diverse global populations. They are up to 1,700 so far.

name: An event
description: Shown here for scale, an event in our universe has three coordinates in space plus one in time.
